    <section xml:id="sec-course-info">
      <title>Course Information</title>
      <p>
        <dl>
          <li>
            <title>Course Description</title>
            <p>
              Linear algebra is one of the most important subjects in mathematics, with applications everywhere from computer science to chemistry to economics to, most recently, machine learning and AI.  It has a very different feel from calculus and, for most students, takes some getting used to.  That said, it is a lot of fun and gives a small glimpse of the larger landscape of mathematics that is out there to learn.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
          </li>
        </dl>
      </p>
      <paragraphs>
        <title>Axioms</title>
        <p>
          Dr. Federico Ardila, a mathematician at San Francisco State University, developed a set of axioms for mathematics education.  I strongly support them, and so have copied them here.  
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Mathematical potential is distributed equally among different groups, irrespective of geographic, demographic, and economic boundaries. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Everyone can have joyful, meaningful, and empowering mathematical experiences. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Mathematics is a powerful, malleable tool that can be shaped and used differently by various communities to serve their needs. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Every student deserves to be treated with dignity and respect.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </paragraphs>
    </section>
